ring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Noers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: variant of   Kors   or of <b>Koerts</b> (also <b>Coerts</b>), a patronymic from the personal name <i>Koert</i>, a short form of   Conrad  , formed with genitival <i>-s</i>.","German: variant of   Kohrs  . Compare   Coers  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kors","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Cornelis, Pieter.","Dutch: from a short form of the personal name <i>Korsten</i> (from Latin <i>Christianus</i>; see   Christian  ) or <i>Korneli(u)s</i> (see   Cornelius  )."]},{"name":"Coers","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin.","Dutch and German: variant of   Koers  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William De Noers was born about 1141, in Great Missenden, Buckinghamshire, England, his father, William de Noers of Missenden, was 32 and his mother, Mrs William Noers De Missenden, was 29. He married Hermione Billard-Nessie. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died before 1185."},"et":{"about 1141–before 1185":"umbes 1141–enne 1185","1141–1185":"1141–1185","1130–1185":"1130–1185","1165–1223":"1165–1223","1168–1184":"116